{"title_page": "Penrose Inquiry", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\nThe '''Penrose Inquiry''' was the [[public inquiry]] into [[hepatitis C]] and [[HIV]] infections from [[NHS Scotland]] treatment with blood and blood products such as [[factor VIII]], often used by people with [[haemophilia]]. The event is often called the Tainted Blood Scandal or Contaminated Blood Scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/world-haemophilia-day-2016-contaminated-blood-scandal-one-biggest-nhs-treatment-disasters-1554831|title=World Haemophilia Day 2016: Contaminated blood scandal one of the biggest NHS treatment disasters|last=Keating|first=Fiona|date=2016-04-16|newspaper=International Business Times UK|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIt was not in the terms of reference of the inquiry to examine events in England,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/terms-of-reference/|title=Terms of Reference|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> a statutory public inquiry has never been held in England.<ref>{{cite court | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=2 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''There has never been any judicial consideration of liability or fault and never any statutory public inquiry.''}}</ref> The Penrose Inquiry was set up by [[Scottish Government]] under the [[Inquiries Act 2005]] and cost \u00a312,123,754.<ref>http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/downloads/1447242115-Penrose%20Inquiry%20-%20Publication%20of%20Costs.pdf</ref> It was announced by [[Nicola Sturgeon]] on 23 April 2008. [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose|The Rt Hon Lord Penrose]] was the chairman of the inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/|title=Penrose Inquiry|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nLord Penrose did not attend the launch of the report which was held on 25 March 2015 in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/blood-scandal-victims-condemn-penrose-inquiry-1-3728511|title=Blood scandal victims condemn Penrose inquiry|website=www.scotsman.com|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> He was reported to have been too ill to attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13206580.Chair_of_Penrose_public_inquiry_seriously_ill/|title=Chair of Penrose public inquiry seriously ill|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nThe final report of the Penrose Inquiry was widely branded a [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] after it made only one recommendation, that steps should be taken to offer blood tests to anyone in Scotland who had a blood transfusion before 1991 and who has not already been tested for hepatitis C. The Inquiry did not apportion blame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/penrose-report-blood-scandal-inquiry-branded-a-whitewash-10134095.html|title=Penrose report: Blood scandal inquiry branded a 'whitewash'|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13207377.Penrose_Inquiry____12m_contaminated_blood_probe_branded_a_whitewash/|title=Penrose Inquiry: \u00a312m contaminated blood probe branded a whitewash|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02mr2ns|title=Victims cry 'whitewash' over Penrose blood infection inquiry, Scotland - BBC News|website=BBC|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/victims-angry-at-blood-inquiry-whitewash-10366299|title=Victims Angry At Blood Inquiry 'Whitewash'|newspaper=Sky News|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref name=whe>{{Cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/603273/Six-year-inquiry-failed-find-full-awful-truth-scandal-tainted-blood|title=Six-year inquiry 'failed to find full awful truth about scandal of tainted blood'|last=Wheeler|first=Caroline|date=2015-09-06|newspaper=Express.co.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\nProfessor John Cash who was a former director of the [[Scottish National Blood Transfusion Service]] said the executives responsible were able to avoid giving evidence. \"Did Lord Penrose get to speak to the people with the real answers? No, he didn\u2019t,\" \"He tried but through no fault of his own he couldn\u2019t get to the truth. He ran into serious problems because the Inquiries Act meant there was a whole area he could not address\".<ref name=whe/>\n\nFive deaths were examined as outlined in the inquiry's terms of reference, these were, Reverend David Black, Mrs Eileen O'Hara, Alexander Black Laing, Neil Mullen and Victor Tamburrini.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/terms-of-reference/|title=Terms of Reference|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> Out of these 5 cases, only 1 of the victims was a Haemophiliac. The 1 haemophilia case was a Hepatitis C infection that occurred in the 1960s, before Factor concentrates were in use, meaning that the case did not relate to the relevant period which is regarded at the mid-1970s\u20131980's.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/dec/17/bse.society|title=A bloody mess|date=2002-12-17|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> None of these examined cases involved HIV infection.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tainted Blood|title=The Penrose Inquiry / Chairman's Statement - 25th March 2015|date=2015-03-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_itTVmzdVTk|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nFollowing the publication of the Penrose Inquiry, [[David Cameron]] became the first British Prime Minister to offer a formal apology for the scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-32041715|title=Penrose inquiry: David Cameron apologises over infected blood|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/health/prime-minister-david-cameron-apologises-8921356|title=Prime Minister David Cameron apologises over contaminated blood scandal|last=Williams|first=Tryst|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=walesonline|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=CampaignTB|title=Prime Minister's Questions : Formal Apology - Wednesday 25th March 2015|date=2015-03-31|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8EcXHg7utr4|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Damages]] have never been paid before or after the inquiry to victims or their families in England or Scotland. Damages have been paid in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hepccomptrib.com/2016/index.php?page=1|title=Irish Hepatitis C Compensation Tribunal|website=www.hepccomptrib.com|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/29m-for-victim-of-blood-product-contamination-434458.html|title=\u20ac2.9m for victim of blood product contamination|date=2016-12-09|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mlaw.ie/solicitors-for/hep-c-a-hiv-compensation-tribunal.html|title=Hep C & HIV Compensation Tribunal - Malcomson Law Solicitors|last=Bannon|first=Ultan|website=www.mlaw.ie|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n\n[[Category:Public inquiries in Scotland]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hepatitis C]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\nThe '''Penrose Inquiry''' was the [[public inquiry]] into [[hepatitis C]] and [[HIV]] infections from [[NHS Scotland]] treatment with blood and blood products such as [[factor VIII]], often used by people with [[haemophilia]]. The event is often called the Tainted Blood Scandal or Contaminated Blood Scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/world-haemophilia-day-2016-contaminated-blood-scandal-one-biggest-nhs-treatment-disasters-1554831|title=World Haemophilia Day 2016: Contaminated blood scandal one of the biggest NHS treatment disasters|last=Keating|first=Fiona|date=2016-04-16|newspaper=International Business Times UK|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIt was not in the terms of reference of the inquiry to examine events in England,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/terms-of-reference/|title=Terms of Reference|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> a statutory public inquiry has never been held in England.<ref>{{cite court | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=2 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''There has never been any judicial consideration of liability or fault and never any statutory public inquiry.''}}</ref> The Penrose Inquiry was set up by [[Scottish Government]] under the [[Inquiries Act 2005]] and cost \u00a312,123,754.<ref>http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/downloads/1447242115-Penrose%20Inquiry%20-%20Publication%20of%20Costs.pdf</ref> It was announced by [[Nicola Sturgeon]] on 23 April 2008. [[George William Penrose, Lord Penrose|The Rt Hon Lord Penrose]] was the chairman of the inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/|title=Penrose Inquiry|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\nLord Penrose did not attend the launch of the report which was held on 25 March 2015 in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/blood-scandal-victims-condemn-penrose-inquiry-1-3728511|title=Blood scandal victims condemn Penrose inquiry|website=www.scotsman.com|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> He was reported to have been too ill to attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13206580.Chair_of_Penrose_public_inquiry_seriously_ill/|title=Chair of Penrose public inquiry seriously ill|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nThe final report of the Penrose Inquiry was widely branded a [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] after it made only one recommendation, that steps should be taken to offer blood tests to anyone in Scotland who had a blood transfusion before 1991 and who has not already been tested for hepatitis C. The Inquiry did not apportion blame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/penrose-report-blood-scandal-inquiry-branded-a-whitewash-10134095.html|title=Penrose report: Blood scandal inquiry branded a 'whitewash'|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13207377.Penrose_Inquiry____12m_contaminated_blood_probe_branded_a_whitewash/|title=Penrose Inquiry: \u00a312m contaminated blood probe branded a whitewash|website=HeraldScotland|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02mr2ns|title=Victims cry 'whitewash' over Penrose blood infection inquiry, Scotland - BBC News|website=BBC|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/victims-angry-at-blood-inquiry-whitewash-10366299|title=Victims Angry At Blood Inquiry 'Whitewash'|newspaper=Sky News|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref name=whe>{{Cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/603273/Six-year-inquiry-failed-find-full-awful-truth-scandal-tainted-blood|title=Six-year inquiry 'failed to find full awful truth about scandal of tainted blood'|last=Wheeler|first=Caroline|date=2015-09-06|newspaper=Express.co.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\nProfessor John Cash who was a former director of the [[Scottish National Blood Transfusion Service]] said the executives responsible were able to avoid giving evidence. \"Did Lord Penrose get to speak to the people with the real answers? No, he didn\u2019t,\" \"He tried but through no fault of his own he couldn\u2019t get to the truth. He ran into serious problems because the Inquiries Act meant there was a whole area he could not address\".<ref name=whe/>\n\nFive deaths were examined as outlined in the inquiry's terms of reference, these were, Reverend David Black, Mrs Eileen O'Hara, Alexander Black Laing, Neil Mullen and Victor Tamburrini.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penroseinquiry.org.uk/terms-of-reference/|title=Terms of Reference|website=www.penroseinquiry.org.uk|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> Out of these 5 cases, only 1 of the victims was a Haemophiliac. The 1 haemophilia case was a Hepatitis C infection that occurred in the 1960s, before Factor concentrates were in use, meaning that the case did not relate to the relevant period which is regarded at the mid-1970s\u20131980's.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/dec/17/bse.society|title=A bloody mess|date=2002-12-17|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> None of these examined cases involved HIV infection.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tainted Blood|title=The Penrose Inquiry / Chairman's Statement - 25th March 2015|date=2015-03-26|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_itTVmzdVTk|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nFollowing the publication of the Penrose Inquiry, [[David Cameron]] became the first British Prime Minister to offer a formal apology for the scandal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-32041715|title=Penrose inquiry: David Cameron apologises over infected blood|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/health/prime-minister-david-cameron-apologises-8921356|title=Prime Minister David Cameron apologises over contaminated blood scandal|last=Williams|first=Tryst|date=2015-03-25|newspaper=walesonline|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=CampaignTB|title=Prime Minister's Questions : Formal Apology - Wednesday 25th March 2015|date=2015-03-31|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8EcXHg7utr4|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n[[Damages]] have never been paid before or after the inquiry to victims or their families in England or Scotland. Damages have been paid in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hepccomptrib.com/2016/index.php?page=1|title=Irish Hepatitis C Compensation Tribunal|website=www.hepccomptrib.com|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/29m-for-victim-of-blood-product-contamination-434458.html|title=\u20ac2.9m for victim of blood product contamination|date=2016-12-09|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mlaw.ie/solicitors-for/hep-c-a-hiv-compensation-tribunal.html|title=Hep C & HIV Compensation Tribunal - Malcomson Law Solicitors|last=Bannon|first=Ultan|website=www.mlaw.ie|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n\n[[Category:Public inquiries in Scotland]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hepatitis C]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Adding \"Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w